      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The function has a time complexity of O(sqrt(n)) because it increments the divisor by 1 in each iteration. However, we can optimize this by incrementing the divisor by 2 in each iteration, which reduces the number of iterations. Here's the optimized function:\n\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    while d * d <= n:\n        while n % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            n //= d\n        d += 2\n    if n > 1:\n        factors.append(n)\n    return factors\n```\nThis version of the function should pass the runtime tests for large inputs. It works by only incrementing the divisor by 2 in each iteration, which reduces the number of iterations. This is because all prime factors of a number must be of the form 2, 3, 5, etc. (i.e., they must be odd). If the divisor is even, then it cannot be a prime factor of the number.",
